    <h2>How We Evaluated These Companies</h2>
    <p>Every insurer on this list was evaluated across five dimensions: financial strength (AM Best rating), product breadth (term, whole, universal, and indexed options), pricing competitiveness for healthy applicants, availability of no-exam or simplified-issue policies, and customer satisfaction based on publicly available complaint ratios from the National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC). No single company dominates every category, which is why matching a company to your specific situation matters more than picking the one at the top of an arbitrary list.</p>
    <p>AM Best ratings deserve special attention because they measure something most review sites ignore: the probability that an insurer will be able to pay claims years or decades from now. An A++ (Superior) rating means the company has the strongest balance sheet and operating performance in the industry. An A+ (Superior) is just one notch below. Anything rated A or higher is considered excellent, and you should be cautious about purchasing a policy from any company rated below A- (Excellent).</p>

